glossopharyngeal)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe parasympathetic innervation of the lacrimal gland is provided by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecranial nerve VII (facial nerve)\u003C/strong\u003E. These fibres originate in the superior salivatory nucleus, travel in the nervus intermedius component of CN VII, and then branch via the greater petrosal nerve to reach the lacrimal gland. This parasympathetic activation of the lacrimal glands is responsible for tear production and maintaining eye moisture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve III (oculomotor)\u003C/strong\u003E provides parasympathetic innervation to the pupillary sphincter and ciliary muscles but has no role in lacrimation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve V (trigeminal)\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the cornea and surrounding facial structures but does not provide parasympathetic supply to the lacrimal gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve VI (abducens)\u003C/strong\u003E is purely motor to the lateral rectus muscle and has no parasympathetic function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial nerve IX (glossopharyngeal)\u003C/strong\u003E provides parasympathetic innervation to the parotid gland but has no role in tear production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these anatomical relationships is crucial in clinical practice, particularly when evaluating patients with facial nerve palsy who may present with dry eye symptoms due to decreased lacrimation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cranial nerve VII (facial nerve) carries parasympathetic fibres that innervate the lacrimal gland via the greater petrosal nerve.","The parasympathetic supply to the lacrimal gland is part of the facial nerve\u0027s secretomotor function.","Damage to CN VII can result in decreased tear production (dry eye)."],"references":["Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Sanders RD. The Trigeminal (V) and Facial (VII) Cranial Nerves: Head and Face Sensation and Movement. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2010 Jan;7(1):13-6. PMID: 20386632; PMCID: PMC2848459."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52140"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16360"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52140"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T18:58:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T18:59:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9051"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66687"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{